    Installed this device only to later be told upon a call to the manufacturer's support desk that the transmitting part of this unit needs to be placed within 20 feet of my router. The problem is just that this unit, as a practical matter, is almost never going to work for anyone.

  • OakMan53
    4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    It works
    Reviewed in the United States on July 15, 2023
    I bought this wi-fi humidistat-thermostat along with a Remington roof-top solar vent fan, and its optional 120v. back up power supply. The product came with no instructions. But the fan and power supply did have good instructions. The fan came with a thermostat, which... See more
    I bought this wi-fi humidistat-thermostat along with a Remington roof-top solar vent fan, and its optional 120v. back up power supply. The product came with no instructions. But the fan and power supply did have good instructions. The fan came with a thermostat, which was attached with a polarized connector. All I had to do was unscrew the existing thermostat and screw in the wi-fi humidistat-thermostat. The SolaCom phone app was mentioned in the Amazon product listing, so I installed it on my phone. I plugged the hub into my router, and my phone app connected with the hub. The app showed an option to add a device, so I clicked on that, and it presented the option of scanning the QR code on the device, or on the packaging. There was no QR code on the package, so I crawled up into the attic and scanned the humidistat-thermostat. It does have a QR code. The device immediately connected with the hub, and I noted the on and off parameters' display screen for both the humidistat and thermostat functions. There's a separate screed to edit the settings. It also has an on-off manual switch, which I operated successfully. The attic fan vents the 1/3rd of my attic that has a crawl space. The rest of the attic is semi-finished and is insulated with ceiling finishing directly on the inside of the rafters. I chose to get the back up power supply because trees shade the fan's solar panel in the mid to late afternoon, and the attic remains hot for 2 to 3 hours after sundown.

    Does not work well; app is skeletal at best
    Reviewed in the United States on November 3, 2022
    EDIT: Magically, the unit started working. I’m happy I was able to make adjustments needed, but another reviewer was right that the hub and receiver at the fan must be very close. This is an enormous design flaw, since routers will not be in an ATTIC. I am lucky to have... See more
    EDIT: Magically, the unit started working. I’m happy I was able to make adjustments needed, but another reviewer was right that the hub and receiver at the fan must be very close. This is an enormous design flaw, since routers will not be in an ATTIC. I am lucky to have previously installed conduit and a mesh network, so plugged directly in to an extender that is below the fan upstairs. It connects *okay* now. It is clear that the receiver is actually using 1980s technology that wireless phones in homes used. What a joke of a product in 2022 for that price. It’s a great fan and product otherwise, so why the terrible add-on?

    ———
    What can I say? It simply doesn’t work. The hub blinks red regardless of settings and such. The instructions are beyond useless.
    They say if a light is blinking red to “unplug” everything to bypass the firewall. This did nothing. It is plugged directly in to our router, which is extremely reliable. The app is horrible. It’s GUI looks like a developer platform, and the only real feature is showing humidistat and temp readings, and allowing changing thresholds. Those are valuable, but it’s like getting water, to live on, from a dirty pond. Valuable…but c’mon. It all doesn’t matter to me, because the hub isn’t connecting properly anyway. What’s bizarre is that I can access it via the app and see sensor readings, so it’s clearly getting some internet correctly. It just can’t save settings and blinks red as well..
